# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: hydraulic-actuators
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulic-actuator] A **hydraulic cylinder** (also called a **linear hydraulic motor, hydraulic actuator,** or **hydraulic ram**) is a mechanical actuator that is used to convert fluid pressure into linear force and motion.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulic-actuator] It has many applications, notably in construction equipment (engineering vehicles), manufacturing machinery, elevators, and civil engineering.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulic-actuator] A hydraulic cylinder is a hydraulic actuator that provides linear motion when hydraulic energy is converted into mechanical movement.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulic-actuator] It can be likened to a muscle in that, when the hydraulic system of a machine is activated, the cylinder is responsible for providing the motion.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulic-actuator] Hydraulic cylinders are powered from pressurized hydraulic fluid, which is incompressible.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulic-actuator] Typically oil is used as hydraulic fluid.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulic-actuator] The hydraulic cylinder consists of a cylinder barrel, in which a piston connected to a piston rod moves back and forth.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulic-actuator] The barrel is closed on one end by the cylinder bottom (also called the cap) and the other end by the cylinder head (also called the gland) where the piston rod comes out of the cylinder.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulic-actuator] The piston divides the inside of the cylinder into two chambers, the bottom chamber (cap end) and the piston rod side chamber (rod end/head-end).
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulic-actuator] Flanges, trunnions, clevises, and lugs are common cylinder mounting end options.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulic-actuator] The piston rod also has mounting attachments to connect the cylinder to the object or machine component that it is pushing or pulling.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulic-actuator] A hydraulic cylinder is the actuator or "motor" side of this system.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulic-actuator] The "generator" side of the hydraulic system is the hydraulic pump which pressurizes and delivers a fixed or regulated flow of oil to the hydraulic cylinder, to move the piston.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulic-actuator] Typically, hydraulic pumps generate power by various energy sources: hand, air, and electric motor, or engine.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulic-actuator] The piston pushes the oil in the other chamber back to the reservoir.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulic-actuator] Actual force measured during piston rod movement may exceed the calculated force by 20% or more due to friction created by seals and mounting end bushings.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulic-actuator] Hydraulic cylinder pistons rods are typically sized according to the force, including friction losses, needed to move a load, while avoiding piston rod buckling load, as can be assessed by ANSI T3.6.37 or ISO/TS 13725.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulic-actuator] Shearing forces at the connection between the piston rod and mounting end or at the hydraulic cylinder base is another factor to consider when determining hydraulic cylinder reliability.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulic-actuator] For double-acting single-rod cylinders, when the input and output pressures are reversed, there is a force difference between the two sides of the piston due to one side of the piston being covered by the rod attached to it.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulic-actuator] The cylinder rod reduces the surface area of the piston and reduces the force that can be applied for the retraction stroke.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulic-actuator] where P is the fluid pressure, Fp is the pulling force, Ap is the piston face area and Ar is the rod cross-section area.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulic-actuator] For double-acting, double-rod cylinders, when the piston surface area is equally covered by a rod of equal size on both sides of the head, there is no force difference.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulic-actuator] Such cylinders typically have their cylinder body affixed to a stationary mount.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulic-actuator] Hydraulic cylinders can be used in any machine where high forces are required, one of the most familiar being earth-moving equipment such as excavators, back hoes and tractors to lift or lower the boom, arm, or bucket.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulic-actuator] Manufacturing is another popular application where they can be found in hydraulic bending machines, metal sheet shearing machines, particle board or plywood making hot press.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulic-actuator] A hydraulic cylinder barrel is the main, high-strength tubular body of a hydraulic actuator that houses the piston, rod, and seals.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulic-actuator] It acts as a pressure vessel containing high-pressure fluid, typically manufactured from honed seamless steel tubes to provide a wear-resistant interior surface for smooth piston movement and seal efficiency.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulic-actuator] The main function of the cap is to enclose the pressure chamber at one end.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulic-actuator] The cap is connected to the body by means of welding, threading, bolts, or tie rods.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulic-actuator] Caps also perform as cylinder mounting components [cap flange, cap trunnion, cap clevis].
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulic-actuator] Capsize is determined based on the bending stress.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulic-actuator] A static seal / o-ring is used in between cap and barrel (except welded construction).
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulic-actuator] The main function of the head is to enclose the pressure chamber from the other end.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulic-actuator] The head contains an integrated rod sealing arrangement or the option to accept a seal gland.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulic-actuator] The head is connected to the body by means of threading, bolts, or tie rods.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulic-actuator] A static seal / o-ring is used in between head and barrel.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulic-actuator] The main function of the piston is to separate the pressure zones inside the barrel.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulic-actuator] The piston is machined with grooves to fit elastomeric or metal seals and bearing elements.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulic-actuator] These seals can be single-acting or double-acting.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulic-actuator] The difference in pressure between the two sides of the piston causes the cylinder to extend and retract.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulic-actuator] The piston is attached to the piston rod by means of threads, bolts, or nuts to transfer the linear motion.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulic-actuator] The piston rod is typically a hard chrome-plated piece of cold-rolled steel that attaches to the piston and extends from the cylinder through the rod-end head.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulic-actuator] In double rod-end cylinders, the actuator has a rod extending from both sides of the piston and out both ends of the barrel.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulic-actuator] The piston rod connects the hydraulic actuator to the machine component doing the work.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulic-actuator] This connection can be in the form of a machine thread or a mounting attachment.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulic-actuator] The piston rod is highly ground and polished to provide a reliable seal and prevent leakage.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulic-actuator] The cylinder head is fitted with seals to prevent the pressurized oil from leaking past the interface between the rod and the head.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulic-actuator] The advantage of a seal gland is easy removal and seal replacement.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulic-actuator] The seal gland contains a primary seal, a secondary seal/buffer seal, bearing elements, a wiper/scraper, and a static seal.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulic-actuator] In some cases, especially in small hydraulic cylinders, the rod gland and the bearing elements are made from a single integral machined part.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulic-actuator] The seals are considered/designed to withstand maximum cylinder working pressure, cylinder speed, operating temperature, working medium, and application.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulic-actuator] Piston seals are dynamic seals, and they can be single-acting or double-acting.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulic-actuator] Generally speaking, Elastomer seals made from nitrile rubber, Polyurethane, or other materials are best in lower temperature environments, while seals made of Fluorocarbon Viton are better for higher temperatures.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulic-actuator] Metallic seals are also available and commonly used cast iron for the seal material.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulic-actuator] Rod seals are dynamic seals and generally are single-acting.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulic-actuator] The compounds of rod seals are nitrile rubber, Polyurethane, or Fluorocarbon Viton.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulic-actuator] Wipers/scrapers are used to eliminate contaminants such as moisture, dirt, and dust, which can cause extensive damage to cylinder walls, rods, seals, and other components.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulic-actuator] The common compound for wipers is polyurethane.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulic-actuator] Metallic scrapers are used for sub-zero temperature applications and applications where foreign materials can deposit on the rod.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulic-actuator] The bearing elements/wear bands are used to eliminate metal to metal contact.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulic-actuator] The wear bands are designed to withstand maximum side loads.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulic-actuator] The primary compounds used for wear bands are filled PTFE, woven fabric reinforced polyester resin, and bronze.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulic-actuator] There are many component parts that make up the internal portion of a hydraulic cylinder.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulic-actuator] All of these pieces combine to create a fully functioning component.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulic-actuator] There are primarily two main styles of hydraulic cylinder construction used in the industry: tie rod-style cylinders and welded body-style cylinders.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulic-actuator] Tie rod style hydraulic cylinders use high strength threaded steel rods to hold the two end caps to the cylinder barrel.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulic-actuator] They are most often seen in industrial factory applications.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulic-actuator] Small-bore cylinders usually have 4 tie rods, and large bore cylinders may require as many as 16 or 20 tie rods to retain the end caps under the tremendous forces produced.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulic-actuator] Tie rod style cylinders can be completely disassembled for service and repair, and they are not always customizable.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulic-actuator] The National Fluid Power Association (NFPA) has standardized the dimensions of hydraulic tie-rod cylinders.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulic-actuator] This enables cylinders from different manufacturers to interchange within the same mountings.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulic-actuator] The barrel is welded directly to the end caps.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulic-actuator] The front rod gland is usually threaded into or bolted to the cylinder barrel, allowing for the piston rod assembly and the rod seals to be removed for service.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulic-actuator] Welded body cylinders have a number of advantages over tie rod-style cylinders.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulic-actuator] Welded cylinders have a narrower body and often a shorter overall length enabling them to fit better into the tight confines of machinery.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulic-actuator] Welded cylinders do not suffer from failure due to tie rod stretch at high pressures and long strokes.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulic-actuator] The welded design also lends itself to customization.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulic-actuator] Special features are easily added to the cylinder body, including special ports, custom mounts, valve manifolds, and so on.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulic-actuator] The smooth outer body of welded cylinders also enables the design of multi-stage telescopic cylinders.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulic-actuator] Welded body hydraulic cylinders dominate the mobile hydraulic equipment market such as construction equipment (excavators, bulldozers, and road graders) and material handling equipment (forklift trucks, telehandlers, and lift-gates).
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulic-actuator] They are also used by heavy industry in cranes, oil rigs, and large off-road vehicles for above-ground mining operations.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulic-actuator] The piston rod of a hydraulic cylinder operates both inside and outside the barrel, and consequently both in and out of the hydraulic fluid and surrounding atmosphere.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulic-actuator] Wear and corrosion-resistant surfaces are desirable on the outer diameter of the piston rod.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulic-actuator] The surfaces are often applied using coating techniques such as Chrome (Nickel) Plating, Lunac 2+ duplex, Laser Cladding, PTA welding and Thermal Spraying.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulic-actuator] These coatings can be finished to the desirable surface roughness (Ra, Rz) where the seals give optimum performance.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulic-actuator] All these coating methods have their specific advantages and disadvantages.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulic-actuator] It is for this reason that coating experts play a crucial role in selecting the optimum surface treatment procedure for protecting Hydraulic Cylinders.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulic-actuator] Cylinders are used in different operational conditions and that makes it a challenge to find the right coating solution.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulic-actuator] In dredging there might be impact from stones or other parts, in saltwater environments, there are extreme corrosion attacks, in off-shore cylinders facing bending and impact in combination with salt water, and in the steel industry, there are high temperatures involved, etc.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulic-actuator] There is no single coating solution that successfully combats all the specific operational wear conditions.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulic-actuator] Every technique has its own benefits and disadvantages.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulic-actuator] Piston rods are generally available in lengths that are cut to suit the application.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulic-actuator] As the common rods have a soft or mild steel core, their ends can be welded or machined for a screw thread.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulic-actuator] The forces on the piston face and the piston head retainer vary depending on which piston head retention system is used.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulic-actuator] If a circlip (or any non-preloaded system) is used, the force acting to separate the piston head and the cylinder shaft shoulder is the applied pressure multiplied by the area of the piston head.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulic-actuator] The piston head and shaft shoulder will separate and the load is fully reacted by the piston head retainer.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulic-actuator] If a preloaded system is used the force between the cylinder shaft and piston head is initially the piston head retainer preload value.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulic-actuator] Once pressure has applied this force will reduce.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulic-actuator] The piston head and cylinder shaft shoulder will remain in contact unless the applied pressure multiplied by the piston head area exceeds the preload.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulic-actuator] The maximum force the piston head retainer will see is the larger of the preload and the applied pressure multiplied by the full piston head area.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulic-actuator] The load on the piston head retainer is greater than the external load, which is due to the reduced shaft size passing through the piston head.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulic-actuator] Increasing this portion of shaft reduces the load on the retainer.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulic-actuator] Side loading is unequal pressure that is not centered on the cylinder rod.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulic-actuator] This off-center strain can lead to bending of the rod in extreme cases, but more commonly causes leaking due to warping the circular seals into an oval shape.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulic-actuator] It can also damage and enlarge the bore hole around the rod and the inner cylinder wall around the piston head, if the rod is pressed hard enough sideways to fully compress and deform the seals to make metal-on-metal scraping contact.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulic-actuator] The strain of side loading can be directly reduced with the use of internal stop tubes which reduce the maximum extension length, leaving some distance between the piston and bore seal, and increasing leverage to resist warping of the seals.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulic-actuator] Double pistons also spread out the forces of side loading while also reducing stroke length.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulic-actuator] Alternately, external sliding guides and hinges can support the load and reduce side loading forces applied directly on the cylinder.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulic-actuator] Mounting methods also play an important role in cylinder performance.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulic-actuator] Generally, fixed mounts on the centerline of the cylinder are best for straight-line force transfer and avoiding wear.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulic-actuator] The length of a hydraulic cylinder is the total of the stroke, the thickness of the piston, the thickness of bottom and head and the length of the connections.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulic-actuator] Often this length does not fit in the machine.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulic-actuator] In that case the piston rod is also used as a piston barrel and a second piston rod is used.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulic-actuator] These kinds of cylinders are called telescopic cylinders.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulic-actuator] If we call a normal rod cylinder single stage, telescopic cylinders are multi-stage units of two, three, four, five, or more stages.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulic-actuator] In general telescopic cylinders are much more expensive than normal cylinders.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulic-actuator] Most telescopic cylinders are single acting (push).
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulic-actuator] Double acting telescopic cylinders must be specially designed and manufactured.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulic-actuator] A hydraulic cylinder without a piston or with a piston without seals is called a plunger cylinder.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulic-actuator] A plunger cylinder can only be used as a pushing cylinder; the maximum force is piston rod area multiplied by pressure.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulic-actuator] This means that a plunger cylinder in general has a relatively thick piston rod.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulic-actuator] A differential cylinder acts like a normal cylinder when pulling.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulic-actuator] If the cylinder however has to push, the oil from the piston rod side of the cylinder is not returned to the reservoir but goes to the bottom side of the cylinder.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulic-actuator] In such a way, the cylinder goes much faster, but the maximum force the cylinder can give is like a plunger cylinder.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulic-actuator] A differential cylinder can be manufactured like a normal cylinder, and only a special control is added.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulic-actuator] The above differential cylinder is also called a regenerative cylinder control circuit.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulic-actuator] This term means that the cylinder is a single rod, double-acting hydraulic cylinder.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulic-actuator] The control circuit includes a valve and piping which during the extension of the piston, conducts the oil from the rod side of the piston to the other side of the piston instead of to the pump’s reservoir.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulic-actuator] The oil which is conducted to the other side of the piston is referred to as the regenerative oil.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulic-actuator] Position sensing hydraulic cylinders eliminate the need for a hollow cylinder rod.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulic-actuator] Instead, an external sensing "bar" using Hall Effect technology senses the position of the cylinder’s piston.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulic-actuator] This is accomplished by the placement of a permanent magnet within the piston.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulic-actuator] The magnet propagates a magnetic field through the steel wall of the cylinder, providing a locating signal to the sensor.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulic-fluid] A **hydraulic fluid** or **hydraulic liquid** is the medium by which power is transferred in hydraulic machinery.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulic-fluid] Common hydraulic fluids are based on mineral oil or water.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulic-fluid] Examples of equipment that might use hydraulic fluids are excavators and backhoes, hydraulic brakes, power steering systems, automatic transmissions, garbage trucks, aircraft flight control systems, lifts, and industrial machinery.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulic-fluid] Hydraulic systems like the ones mentioned above will work most efficiently if the hydraulic fluid used has zero compressibility.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulic-fluid] The primary function of a hydraulic fluid is to convey power.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulic-fluid] In use, however, there are other important functions of hydraulic fluid such as protection of the hydraulic machine components.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulic-fluid] Although many liquids can be used, such as water, almost all hydraulic fluids are less corrosive and more viscous.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulic-fluid] The petrochemical mineral oil is the predominant component, the particular type being dictated by viscosity.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulic-fluid] Poly alpha olefins, which are petroleum-derived synthetic lubricating oils, are mixed with the mineral oil.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulic-fluid] Other base stocks are used for specialty applications, such as for fire resistance and extreme temperature applications.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulic-fluid] Some examples include: glycol ethers, organophosphate ester, polyalphaolefin, propylene glycol, and silicone oils.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulic-fluid] Hydraulic fluids can contain a wide range of additives as corrosion inhibitors (incl acid scavengers), anti-erosion additives, etc.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulic-fluid] NaK-77, a eutectic alloy of sodium and potassium, can be used as a hydraulic fluid in high-temperature and high-radiation environments, for temperature ranges of 10 to 1,400 °F (−12 to 760 °C).
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulic-fluid] Its bulk modulus at 1,000 °F (538 °C) is 310,000 psi (2.14 GPa), higher than of a hydraulic oil at room temperature.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulic-fluid] Its lubricity is poor, so positive-displacement pumps are unsuitable and centrifugal pumps have to be used.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulic-fluid] The addition of caesium shifts the useful temperature range to −95 to 1,300 °F (−71 to 704 °C).
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulic-fluid] The NaK-77 alloy was tested in hydraulic and fluidic systems for the Supersonic Low Altitude Missile.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulic-fluid] Environmentally sensitive applications (e.g. farm tractors and marine dredging) may benefit from using biodegradable hydraulic fluids.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulic-fluid] Natural oils such as rapeseed are used as base stocks for fluids where biodegradability and renewable sources are considered important, e.g. when there is the risk of an oil spill.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulic-fluid] Typically these oils are available as ISO 32, ISO 46, and ISO 68 specification oils.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulic-fluid] ASTM standards ASTM-D-6006, Guide for Assessing Biodegradability of Hydraulic Fluids and ASTM-D-6046, Standard Classification of Hydraulic Fluids for Environmental Impact are relevant.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulic-fluid] Because industrial hydraulic systems operate at hundreds to thousands of PSI and temperatures reaching hundreds of degrees Celsius, severe injuries and death can result from component failures and care must always be taken when performing maintenance on hydraulic systems.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulic-fluid] Fire resistance is a property available with specialized fluids.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulic-fluid] Water-glycol and polyol-ester are some of these specialized fluids that contain excellent thermal and hydrolytic properties, which aid in fire resistance.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulic-fluid] Brake fluid is a subtype of hydraulic fluid with high boiling point, both when new (specified by the equilibrium boiling point) and after absorption of water vapor (specified by wet boiling point).
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulic-fluid] Under the heat of braking, both free water and water vapor in a braking system can boil into a compressible vapor, resulting in brake failure.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulic-fluid] Glycol-ether based fluids are hygroscopic, and absorbed moisture will greatly reduce the boiling point over time.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulic-fluid] Mineral oil and silicone based fluids are not hygroscopic.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulic-fluid] Power steering fluid is a sub type of hydraulic fluid.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulic-fluid] Most are mineral oil or silicone based fluids, while some use automatic transmission fluid, made from synthetic base oil.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulic-fluid] Automatic transmissions use fluids for their lubrication, cooling and hydraulic properties for viscous couplings.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulic-fluid] Use of the wrong type of fluid can lead to failure of the power steering pump.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulic-fluid] As aircraft performance increased in the mid-20th century, the amount of force required to operate mechanical flight controls became excessive, and hydraulic systems were introduced to reduce pilot effort.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulic-fluid] The hydraulic actuators are controlled by valves; these in turn are operated directly by input from the aircrew (hydro-mechanical) or by computers obeying control laws (fly by wire).
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulic-fluid] Hydraulic power is used for other purposes.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulic-fluid] It can be stored in accumulators to start an auxiliary power unit (APU) for self-starting the aircraft's main engines.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulic-fluid] Many aircraft equipped with the M61 family of cannon use hydraulic power to drive the gun system, permitting reliable high rates of fire.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulic-fluid] The hydraulic power itself comes from pumps driven by the engines directly, or by electrically driven pumps.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulic-fluid] In modern commercial aircraft these are electrically driven pumps; should all the engines fail in flight the pilot will deploy a propeller-driven electric generator called a *Ram-Air Turbine* (RAT) which is concealed under the fuselage.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulic-fluid] This provides electrical power for the hydraulic pumps and control systems as power is no longer available from the engines.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulic-fluid] In that system and others, electric pumps can provide both redundancy and the means of operating hydraulic systems without the engines operating, which can be very useful during maintenance.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulic-fluid] Special, stringent care is required when handling aircraft hydraulic fluid, as it is critical to flight safety that it stay free from contamination.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulic-fluid] It is also necessary to strictly adhere to authorized references when servicing or repairing any aircraft system.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulic-fluid] Samples from aircraft hydraulic systems are taken during heavy aircraft maintenance checks (primarily C and D checks) to check contamination.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulic-fluid] Military Spec 1246C is one fluid contamination specification.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulic-fluid] The ISO fluid contamination scale assigns a contamination category based on particle size count and distribution.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulic-fluid] The properties of HLP 32 hydraulic oil make it ideal for lubricating machine tools.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulic-fluid] Synthetic hydrocarbon base: These synthetic fluids are compatible with mineral-base hydraulic fluids and were developed to address the low flash point draw back of mineral based hydraulic fluids.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulic-fluid] Commonly used hydraulic oil viscosities fall under the ISO VG (Viscosity Grade) classification system, which is based on the oil's kinematic viscosity at 40 °C (104 °F).
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulic-fluid] Additional viscosities such as the following, are also used, but less frequently or for specific low/high-temperature applications.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulic-machinery] Hydraulic systems, like pneumatic systems, are based on Pascal's law which states that any pressure applied to a fluid inside a closed system will transmit that pressure equally everywhere and in all directions.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulic-machinery] A hydraulic system uses an incompressible liquid as its fluid, rather than a compressible gas.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulic-machinery] One drawback, compared to machines using gears and shafts, is that any transmission of power results in some losses due to resistance of fluid flow through the piping.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulic-machinery] Joseph Bramah patented the hydraulic press in 1795.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulic-machinery] While working at Bramah's shop, Henry Maudslay suggested a cup leather packing.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulic-machinery] Because it produced superior results, the hydraulic press eventually displaced the steam hammer for metal forging.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulic-machinery] To supply large-scale power that was impractical for individual steam engines, central station hydraulic systems were developed.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulic-machinery] Hydraulic power was used to operate cranes and other machinery in British ports and elsewhere in Europe.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulic-machinery] The largest hydraulic system was in London.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulic-machinery] Hydraulic power was used extensively in Bessemer steel production.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulic-machinery] Hydraulic power was also used for elevators and to operate canal locks and rotating sections of bridges.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulic-machinery] Some of these systems remained in use well into the twentieth century.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulic-machinery] Harry Franklin Vickers was called the "Father of Industrial Hydraulics" by ASME.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulic-machinery] In normal cases, hydraulic ratios are combined with a mechanical force or torque ratio for optimum machine designs such as boom movements and track drives for an excavator.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulic-machinery] Cylinder C1 is one inch in radius, and cylinder C2 is ten inches in radius.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulic-machinery] If the force exerted on C1 is 10 lbf, the force exerted by C2 is 1000 lbf because C2 is a hundred times larger in area (*S* = π*r*²) as C1.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulic-machinery] The downside to this is that you have to move C1 a hundred inches to move C2 one inch.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulic-machinery] The most common use for this is the classical hydraulic jack where a pumping cylinder with a small diameter is connected to the lifting cylinder with a large diameter.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulic-machinery] This combination is actually the same type of force multiplication as the cylinder example, just that the linear force in this case is a rotary force, defined as torque.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulic-machinery] Both these examples are usually referred to as a hydraulic transmission or hydrostatic transmission involving a certain hydraulic "gear ratio".
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulic-machinery] A hydraulic circuit is a system comprising an interconnected set of discrete components that transport liquid.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulic-machinery] The purpose of this system may be to control where fluid flows (as in a network of tubes of coolant in a thermodynamic system) or to control fluid pressure (as in hydraulic amplifiers).
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulic-machinery] For example, hydraulic machinery uses hydraulic circuits (in which hydraulic fluid is pushed, under pressure, through hydraulic pumps, pipes, tubes, hoses, hydraulic motors, hydraulic cylinders, and so on) to move heavy loads.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulic-machinery] The approach of describing a fluid system in terms of discrete components is inspired by the success of electrical circuit theory.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulic-machinery] Just as electric circuit theory works when elements are discrete and linear, hydraulic circuit theory works best when the elements (passive components such as pipes or transmission lines or active components such as power packs or pumps) are discrete and linear.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulic-machinery] This usually means that hydraulic circuit analysis works best for long, thin tubes with discrete pumps, as found in chemical process flow systems or microscale devices.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulic-machinery] For the hydraulic fluid to do work, it must flow to the actuator and/or motors, then return to a reservoir.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulic-machinery] The fluid is then filtered and re-pumped.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulic-machinery] The path taken by hydraulic fluid is called a hydraulic circuit of which there are several types.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulic-machinery] Closed loop systems in mobile equipment are generally used for the transmission as an alternative to mechanical and hydrodynamic (converter) transmissions.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulic-machinery] The advantage is a stepless gear ratio (continuously variable speed/torque) and a more flexible control of the gear ratio depending on the load and operating conditions.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulic-machinery] The hydrostatic transmission is generally limited to around 200 kW maximum power, as the total cost gets too high at higher power compared to a hydrodynamic transmission.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulic-machinery] Large wheel loaders for instance and heavy machines are therefore usually equipped with converter transmissions.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulic-machinery] The function is similar to stalling a converter gearbox at high engine rpm.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulic-machinery] The inch function affects the preset characteristics for the 'hydrostatic' gear ratio versus diesel engine rpm.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulic-machinery] The average $\Delta p_{LS}$ is around 2 MPa (290 psi).
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulic-machinery] If the pump flow is high the extra loss can be considerable.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulic-machinery] The power loss also increases if the load pressures vary a lot.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulic-machinery] The cylinder areas, motor displacements and mechanical torque arms must be designed to match load pressure in order to bring down the power losses.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulic-machinery] Pump pressure always equals the maximum load pressure when several functions are run simultaneously and the power input to the pump equals the (max. load pressure + Δ*p*LS) x sum of flow.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulic-machinery] Load sensing *with up-stream compensator* for each connected directional valve.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulic-machinery] Load sensing *with down-stream compensator* for each connected directional valve.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulic-machinery] Load sensing *with a combination of up-stream and down-stream compensators*.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulic-machinery] Load sensing with synchronized, both electric controlled pump displacement and electric controlled valve flow area for faster response, increased stability and fewer system losses.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulic-machinery] This is a new type of LS-system, not yet fully developed.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulic-machinery] Technically the down-stream mounted compensator in a valve block can physically be mounted "up-stream", but work as a down-stream compensator.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulic-machinery] System type (3) gives the advantage that activated functions are synchronized independent of pump flow capacity.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulic-machinery] The flow relation between two or more activated functions remains independent of load pressures, even if the pump reaches the maximum swivel angle.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulic-machinery] This feature is important for machines that often run with the pump at maximum swivel angle and with several activated functions that must be synchronized in speed, such as with excavators.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulic-machinery] With the type (4) system, the functions with *up-stream* compensators have priority, for example the steering function for a wheel loader.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulic-machinery] The system type with down-stream compensators usually have a unique trademark depending on the manufacturer of the valves, for example "LSC" (Linde Hydraulics), "LUDV" (Bosch Rexroth Hydraulics) and "Flowsharing" (Parker Hydraulics) etc.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulic-machinery] No official standardized name for this type of system has been established but flowsharing is a common name for it.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulic-machinery] Hydraulic pumps supply fluid to the components in the system.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulic-machinery] Pressure in the system develops in reaction to the load.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulic-machinery] Hence, a pump rated for 5,000 psi is capable of maintaining flow against a load of 5,000 psi.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulic-machinery] Pumps have a power density about ten times greater than an electric motor (by volume).
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulic-machinery] They are powered by an electric motor or an engine, connected through gears, belts, or a flexible elastomeric coupling to reduce vibration.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulic-machinery] Piston pumps are more expensive than gear or vane pumps, but provide longer life operating at higher pressure, with difficult fluids and longer continuous duty cycles.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulic-machinery] Piston pumps make up one half of a hydrostatic transmission.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulic-machinery] The spool has a central (neutral) position maintained with springs; in this position the supply fluid is blocked, or returned to tank.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulic-machinery] Sliding the spool to one side routes the hydraulic fluid to an actuator and provides a return path from the actuator to tank.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulic-machinery] When the spool is moved to the opposite direction the supply and return paths are switched.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulic-machinery] When the spool is allowed to return to neutral (center) position the actuator fluid paths are blocked, locking it in position.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulic-machinery] Directional control valves are usually designed to be stackable, with one valve for each hydraulic cylinder, and one fluid input supplying all the valves in the stack.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulic-machinery] Tolerances are very tight in order to handle the high pressure and avoid leaking, spools typically have a clearance with the housing of less than a thousandth of an inch (25 μm).
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulic-machinery] The valve block will be mounted to the machine's frame with a *three point* pattern to avoid distorting the valve block and jamming the valve's sensitive components.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulic-machinery] The spool position may be actuated by mechanical levers, hydraulic *pilot* pressure, or solenoids which push the spool left or right.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulic-machinery] A seal allows part of the spool to protrude outside the housing, where it is accessible to the actuator.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulic-machinery] The main valve block is usually a stack of *off the shelf* directional control valves chosen by flow capacity and performance.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulic-machinery] Some valves are designed to be proportional (flow rate proportional to valve position), while others may be simply on-off.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulic-machinery] The control valve is one of the most expensive and sensitive parts of a hydraulic circuit.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulic-machinery] The hydraulic fluid reservoir holds excess hydraulic fluid to accommodate volume changes from: cylinder extension and contraction, temperature driven expansion and contraction, and leaks.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulic-machinery] The reservoir is also designed to aid in separation of air from the fluid and also work as a heat accumulator to cover losses in the system when peak power is used.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulic-machinery] Reservoirs can also help separate dirt and other particulate from the oil, as the particulate will generally settle to the bottom of the tank.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulic-machinery] Some designs include dynamic flow channels on the fluid's return path that allow for a smaller reservoir.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulic-machinery] Accumulators are a common part of hydraulic machinery.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulic-machinery] Their function is to store energy by using pressurized gas.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulic-machinery] One type is a tube with a floating piston.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulic-machinery] On the one side of the piston there is a charge of pressurized gas, and on the other side is the fluid.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulic-machinery] Examples of accumulator uses are backup power for steering or brakes, or to act as a shock absorber for the hydraulic circuit.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulic-machinery] Also known as *tractor fluid*, hydraulic fluid is the life of the hydraulic circuit.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulic-machinery] It is usually petroleum oil with various additives.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulic-machinery] Some hydraulic machines require fire resistant fluids, depending on their applications.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulic-machinery] In some factories where food is prepared, either an edible oil or water is used as a working fluid for health and safety reasons.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulic-machinery] In addition to transferring energy, hydraulic fluid needs to lubricate components, suspend contaminants and metal filings for transport to the filter, and to function well to several hundred degrees Fahrenheit or Celsius.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulic-machinery] Filters are an important part of hydraulic systems which removes the unwanted particles from fluid.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulic-machinery] Metal particles are continually produced by mechanical components and need to be removed along with other contaminants.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulic-machinery] Filters may be positioned in many locations.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulic-machinery] The filter may be located between the reservoir and the pump intake.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulic-machinery] Blockage of the filter will cause cavitation and possibly failure of the pump.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulic-machinery] Sometimes the filter is located between the pump and the control valves.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulic-machinery] This arrangement is more expensive, since the filter housing is pressurized, but eliminates cavitation problems and protects the control valve from pump failures.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulic-machinery] The third common filter location is just before the return line enters the reservoir.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulic-machinery] This location is relatively insensitive to blockage and does not require a pressurized housing, but contaminants that enter the reservoir from external sources are not filtered until passing through the system at least once.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulic-machinery] Filters are used from 7 micron to 15 micron depending upon the viscosity grade of the hydraulic oil.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulic-machinery] Tubes and pipes for hydraulic n applications are internally oiled before the system is commissioned.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulic-machinery] Usually steel piping is painted outside.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulic-machinery] Where flare and other couplings are used, the paint is removed under the nut, and is a location where corrosion can begin.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulic-machinery] For this reason, in marine applications most piping is stainless steel.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulic-machinery] Components of a hydraulic system [sources (e.g. pumps), controls (e.g. valves) and actuators (e.g. cylinders)] need connections that will contain and direct the hydraulic fluid without leaking or losing the pressure that makes them work.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulic-machinery] In some cases, the components can be made to bolt together with fluid paths built-in.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulic-machinery] In more cases, though, rigid tubing or flexible hoses are used to direct the flow from one component to the next.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulic-machinery] Each component has entry and exit points for the fluid involved (called ports) sized according to how much fluid is expected to pass through it.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulic-machinery] There are a number of standardized methods in use to attach the hose or tube to the component.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulic-machinery] Some are intended for ease of use and service, others are better for higher system pressures or control of leakage.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulic-machinery] The most common method, in general, is to provide in each component a female-threaded port, on each hose or tube a female-threaded captive nut, and use a separate adapter fitting with matching male threads to connect the two.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulic-machinery] This is functional, economical to manufacture, and easy to service.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulic-machinery] Elastomeric seals (O-ring boss and face seal) are the most common types of seals in heavy equipment and are capable of reliably sealing more than 6,000 psi (41 MPa) of fluid pressure.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulic-pump] A **hydraulic pump** is a mechanical source of power that converts mechanical power into hydraulic energy (hydrostatic energy i.e. flow, pressure).
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulic-pump] Hydraulic pumps are used in hydraulic drive systems and can be hydrostatic or hydrodynamic.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulic-pump] They generate flow with enough power to overcome pressure induced by a load at the pump outlet.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulic-pump] When a hydraulic pump operates, it creates a vacuum at the pump inlet, which forces liquid from the reservoir into the inlet line to the pump, and by mechanical action delivers this liquid to the pump outlet and forces it into the hydraulic system.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulic-pump] Hydrodynamic pumps are more frequent in day-to-day life.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulic-pump] Hydrostatic pumps of various types all work on the principle of Pascal's law of fluid-pressure transmission.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulic-pump] Gear pumps (with external teeth) (fixed displacement) are simple and economical pumps.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulic-pump] The swept volume or displacement of gear pumps for hydraulics will be between about 1 to 200 milliliters.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulic-pump] They have the lowest volumetric efficiency ( $\eta _{v}\approx 90\%$ ) of all three basic pump types (gear, vane and piston pumps) These pumps create pressure through the meshing of the gear teeth, which forces fluid around the gears to pressurize the outlet side.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulic-pump] Some gear pumps can be quite noisy, compared to other types, but modern gear pumps are highly reliable and much quieter than older models.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulic-pump] This is in part due to designs incorporating split gears, helical gear teeth and higher precision/quality tooth profiles that mesh and unmesh more smoothly, reducing pressure ripple and related detrimental problems.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulic-pump] Another positive attribute of the gear pump is that catastrophic breakdown is a lot less common than in most other types of hydraulic pumps.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulic-pump] This is because the gears gradually wear down the housing and/or main bushings, reducing the volumetric efficiency of the pump gradually until it is all but useless.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulic-pump] This often happens long before wear and causes the unit to seize or break down.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulic-pump] Hydraulic gear pumps are used in various applications where there are different requirements such as lifting, lowering, opening, closing, or rotating, and they are expected to be safe and long-lasting.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulic-pump] A rotary vane pump is a positive-displacement pump that consists of vanes mounted to a rotor that rotates inside a cavity.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulic-pump] In some cases these vanes can have variable length and/or be tensioned to maintain contact with the walls as the pump rotates.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulic-pump] A critical element in vane pump design is how the vanes are pushed into contact with the pump housing, and how the vane tips are machined at this very point.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulic-pump] Several type of "lip" designs are used, and the main objective is to provide a tight seal between the inside of the housing and the vane, and at the same time to minimize wear and metal-to-metal contact.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulic-pump] Forcing the vane out of the rotating centre and towards the pump housing is accomplished using spring-loaded vanes, or more traditionally, vanes loaded hydrodynamically (via the pressurized system fluid).
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulic-pump] Screw pumps (fixed displacement) consist of two Archimedes' screws that intermesh and are enclosed within the same chamber.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulic-pump] These pumps are used for high flows at relatively low pressure (max 100 bars (10,000 kPa)).
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulic-pump] They were used on board ships where a constant pressure hydraulic system extended through the whole ship, especially to control ball valves but also to help drive the steering gear and other systems.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulic-pump] The advantage of the screw pumps is the low sound level of these pumps; however, the efficiency is not high.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulic-pump] The major problem of screw pumps is that the hydraulic reaction force is transmitted in a direction that's axially opposed to the direction of the flow.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulic-pump] 2. create a hydraulic balance by directing a hydraulic force to a piston under the rotor.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulic-pump] Bent axis pumps, axial piston pumps and motors using the bent axis principle, fixed or adjustable displacement, exists in two different basic designs.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulic-pump] These have the best efficiency of all pumps.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulic-pump] Although in general, the largest displacements are approximately one litre per revolution, if necessary a two-liter swept volume pump can be built.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulic-pump] Often variable-displacement pumps are used so that the oil flow can be adjusted carefully.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulic-pump] These pumps can in general work with a working pressure of up to 350–420 bars in continuous work.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulic-pump] This makes them potentially hugely power saving compared to other constant flow pumps in systems where prime mover/diesel/electric motor rotational speed is constant and required fluid flow is non-constant.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulic-pump] A radial piston pump is a form of hydraulic pump.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulic-pump] The working pistons extend in a radial direction symmetrically around the drive shaft, in contrast to the axial piston pump.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulics] Rooted in fluid mechanics hydraulics is used to govern the use of energy via pressurized liquids.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulics] It has been part of human history since ancient times.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulics] Hydraulic topics range through some parts of science and most engineering modules.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulics] Fluid mechanics provides the theoretical foundation for hydraulics, which focuses on applied engineering using the properties of fluids.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulics] In its fluid power applications, hydraulics is used for the generation, control, and transmission of power by the use of pressurized liquids.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulics] Hydraulic topics range through some parts of science and most of engineering modules, and they cover concepts such as pipe flow, dam design, fluidics, and fluid control circuitry.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulics] The principles of hydraulics are naturally in use in the human body within the vascular system and erectile tissue.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulics] Free surface hydraulics is the branch of hydraulics dealing with free surface flow, such as occurring in rivers, canals, lakes, estuaries, and seas.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulics] Its sub-field open-channel flow studies the flow in open channels.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulics] At a very basic level, hydraulics is the liquid counterpart of pneumatics, which concerns gases.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulics] Early uses of water power date back to Mesopotamia and ancient Egypt, where irrigation has been used since the 6th millennium BC and water clocks have been used since the early 2nd millennium BC.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulics] Other early examples of water power include the Qanat system in ancient Persia, the Turpan water system in ancient Central Asia, and the Piedras Bolas aqueduct in ancient Mexico.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulics] The Maya at Palenque (in modern-day Chiapas, Mexico) engineered the first known pressurized water system in the Americas.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulics] By constructing a subterranean aqueduct (the Piedras Bolas aqueduct) that narrowed significantly at the downstream end, they utilized hydraulic principles to create water pressure capable of shooting water upwards to a height of 6 meters (20 ft).
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulics] This system was likely used for fountains or sanitary purposes, operating without the need for mechanical pumps.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulics] In the Persian Empire or previous entities in Persia, the Persians constructed an intricate system of water mills, canals and dams known as the Shushtar Historical Hydraulic System.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulics] The project, commenced by Achaemenid king Darius the Great and finished by a group of Roman engineers captured by Sassanian king Shapur I, has been referred to by UNESCO as "a masterpiece of creative genius".
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulics] They were also the inventors of the Qanat, an underground aqueduct, around the 9th century BC.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulics] Several of Iran's large, ancient gardens were irrigated thanks to Qanats.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulics] The Qanat spread to neighboring areas, including the Armenian highlands.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulics] There, starting in the early 8th century BC, the Kingdom of Urartu undertook significant hydraulic works, such as the Menua canal.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulics] The earliest evidence of water wheels and watermills dates back to the ancient Near East in the 4th century BC, specifically in the Persian Empire before 350 BC in the regions of Iraq, Iran, and Egypt.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulics] In ancient China there were Sunshu Ao (6th century BC), Ximen Bao (5th century BC), Du Shi (circa 31 AD), Zhang Heng (78 – 139 AD), and Ma Jun (200 – 265 AD), while medieval China had Su Song (1020 – 1101 AD) and Shen Kuo (1031–1095).
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulics] Du Shi employed a waterwheel to power the bellows of a blast furnace producing cast iron.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulics] Zhang Heng was the first to employ hydraulics to provide motive power in rotating an armillary sphere for astronomical observation.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulics] In ancient Sri Lanka, hydraulics were widely used in the ancient kingdoms of Anuradhapura and Polonnaruwa.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulics] The discovery of the principle of the valve tower, or valve pit, (Bisokotuwa in Sinhalese) for regulating the escape of water is credited to ingenuity more than 2,000 years ago.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulics] By the first century AD, several large-scale irrigation works had been completed.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulics] Macro- and micro-hydraulics to provide for domestic horticultural and agricultural needs, surface drainage and erosion control, ornamental and recreational water courses and retaining structures and also cooling systems were in place in Sigiriya, Sri Lanka.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulics] The citadel on the massive rock at the site includes cisterns for collecting water.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulics] Large ancient reservoirs of Sri Lanka are Kalawewa (King Dhatusena), Parakrama Samudra (King Parakrama Bahu), Tisa Wewa (King Dutugamunu), and Minneriya (King Mahasen).
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulics] In Ancient Greece, the Greeks constructed sophisticated water and hydraulic power systems.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulics] An example is a construction by Eupalinos, under a public contract, of a watering channel for Samos, the Tunnel of Eupalinos.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulics] An early example of the usage of a hydraulic wheel, likely the earliest in Europe, is the Perachora wheel (3rd century BC).
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulics] In Greco-Roman Egypt, the construction of the first hydraulic machine automata by Ctesibius (flourished c.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulics] Hero describes several working machines using hydraulic power, such as the force pump, which is known from many Roman sites as having been used for raising water and in fire engines.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulics] In the Roman Empire, different hydraulic applications were developed, including public water supplies, innumerable aqueducts, power using watermills and hydraulic mining.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulics] They were among the first to make use of the siphon to carry water across valleys, and used hushing on a large scale to prospect for and then extract metal ores.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulics] They used lead widely in plumbing systems for domestic and public supply, such as feeding thermae.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulics] Hydraulic mining was used in the gold-fields of northern Spain, which was conquered by Augustus in 25 BC.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulics] The alluvial gold mine of Las Medulas was one of the largest of their mines.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulics] At least seven long aqueducts worked it, and the water streams were used to erode the soft deposits, and then wash the tailings for the valuable gold content.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulics] In the Muslim world during the Islamic Golden Age and Arab Agricultural Revolution (8th–13th centuries), engineers made wide use of hydropower as well as early uses of tidal power, and large hydraulic factory complexes.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulics] A variety of water-powered industrial mills were used in the Islamic world, including fulling mills, gristmills, paper mills, hullers, sawmills, ship mills, stamp mills, steel mills, sugar mills, and tide mills.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulics] By the 11th century, every province throughout the Islamic world had these industrial mills in operation, from Al-Andalus and North Africa to the Middle East and Central Asia.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulics] Muslim engineers also used water turbines, employed gears in watermills and water-raising machines, and pioneered the use of dams as a source of water power, used to provide additional power to watermills and water-raising machines.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulics] Al-Jazari (1136–1206) described designs for 50 devices, many of them water-powered, in his book, *The Book of Knowledge of Ingenious Mechanical Devices*, including water clocks, a device to serve wine, and five devices to lift water from rivers or pools.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulics] These include an endless belt with jugs attached and a reciprocating device with hinged valves.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulics] The earliest programmable machines were water-powered devices developed in the Muslim world.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulics] A music sequencer, a programmable musical instrument, was the earliest type of programmable machine.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulics] The first music sequencer was an automated water-powered flute player invented by the Banu Musa brothers, described in their *Book of Ingenious Devices*, in the 9th century.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulics] In 1206, Al-Jazari invented water-powered programmable automata/robots.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulics] He described four automaton musicians, including drummers operated by a programmable drum machine, where they could be made to play different rhythms and different drum patterns.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulics] During the mid 16th century, Italian engineer Giuseppe Ceredi advanced the design of the Archimedean screw pump, applying mathematical principles to improve its efficiency for irrigation and drainage and secured a patent for his developments.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulics] Ceredi's innovations, documented in *Tre discorsi sopra il modo d'alzar acque da' luoghi bassi* (1567), led to the widespread adoption of the technology throughout Southern Europe.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulics] In 1619 Benedetto Castelli, a student of Galileo Galilei, published the book *Della Misura dell'Acque Correnti* or "On the Measurement of Running Waters," one of the foundations of modern hydrodynamics.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulics] He served as a chief consultant to the Pope on hydraulic projects, i.e., management of rivers in the Papal States, beginning in 1626.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulics] The science and engineering of water in Italy from 1500-1800 in books and manuscripts is presented in an illustrated catalog published in 2022.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulics] Blaise Pascal (1623–1662) studied fluid hydrodynamics and hydrostatics, centered on the principles of hydraulic fluids.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulics] Pascal's law or principle states that for an incompressible fluid at rest, the difference in pressure is proportional to the difference in height, and this difference remains the same whether or not the overall pressure of the fluid is changed by applying an external force.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulics] This implies that by increasing the pressure at any point in a confined fluid, there is an equal increase at every other end in the container, i.e., any change in pressure applied at any point of the liquid is transmitted undiminished throughout the fluids.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulics] A French physician, Poiseuille (1797–1869) researched the flow of blood through the body and discovered an important law governing the rate of flow with the diameter of the tube in which flow occurred.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulics] Several cities developed citywide hydraulic power networks in the 19th century, to operate machinery such as lifts, cranes, capstans and the like.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulics] Joseph Bramah (1748–1814) was an early innovator and William Armstrong (1810–1900) perfected the apparatus for power delivery on an industrial scale.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulics] In London, the London Hydraulic Power Company was a major supplier.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulics] Its pipes serving large parts of the West End of London, City and the Docks, but there were schemes restricted to single enterprises such as docks and railway goods yards.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulics] After students understand the basic principles of hydraulics, some teachers use a hydraulic analogy to help students learn other things.
[src:hydraulic-actuators/hydraulics] Assuming an incompressible fluid or a "very large" ratio of compressibility to contained fluid volume, a finite rate of pressure rise requires that any net flow into the collected fluid volume create a volumetric change.
